I never really knew how much of a habit my phone and social media was for me, but found out after I broke my phone in an area that wasn’t so easy to find a replacement. I definitely felt a little lost for a while, having no idea how to fill all those little in between moments. After a week without a phone, I finally made it to a town to pick up a new phone and rejoin the world. Kind of.
•
Once I had my phone back, I found out how strong dual authentication is. I went through all the steps to recover, but I was still locked out of Instagram and out of options on my end. After a while, Instagram finally sent me a password reset and I was able to log back in.
•
By that time, I was starting up for a long trip on the road and had far less time on my hands. Now that I’m back home, I’m excited to show you what I’ve been up to!
•
This was taken when I was phone-less and completely disconnected from the modern world. Apparently I was disconnected from my brain too and decided my tripod wasn’t necessary since I wasn’t going to be there during low light. But when you want to place a person in the frame to show off scale and you are the only person around, tripods are very useful. After a while of trying to setup the backpack as a tripod, one last group hiked through and luckily I was able to convince one of them to pose at the top!

I can't wait to get back here for my first night photography workshop of the year with @missjessbess@missjessbess and @distantlightphotos!

Interested in improving your photography skills, exploring ghost towns and meeting other passionate photographers? Click the link in my bio for more details about my upcoming workshop in Mojave Preserve!

This was an adventure I’ll never forget! We spent quite a bit of the trip rerouting and running from weather, but planned trips that change into adventures always seem to be the ones that stick with me for a long time.
•
I don’t think I have ever had a trip more planned out down to the finest of details like I had planned for the week in Escalante, which made all the curveballs that much more fun. 😅
•
Murphy’s Law was in full effect. Anything that could go wrong definitely did. I wouldn’t even know where to begin to try to catch you up on everything that happened, so check out my stories this week to see all the mishaps and BTS from my adventure with @missjessbess, @distantlightphotos and @robertoleysyckcreations!

Through all the trials and tribulations of adventuring to remote locations in inclement weather and tough conditions, I often have to remind myself that hey, this is what it’s all about!! 

Always looking on the bright side of life and trying to be optimistic while facing challenges and overcoming obstacles can be a whole lot of fun and so fulfilling, especially when it’s with people you care about. 

That’s what happened during our trip to Escalante, then diverting to chase snow in White Pocket with @ryantoswald @missjessbess @distantlightphotos 
It was rough, with the normal lack of sleep, awful mud, freezing cold, and snow soaked clothing and gear… but we never would have experienced and captured moments like these!

One reason I love the Utah Badlands is the variety of landscapes to photograph. On top of grand vistas and some of the darkest skies on this planet, there are incredible textures and mud cracks right below your feet. Up, down and all around always sends my ADD into overdrive and I can’t ever seem to get enough of this place!
•
Do you want to explore a photographers playground full of buttes, textures and one of the darkest skies we’ve ever seen? Check out the link in my bio to join me and @missjessbess for an unforgettable adventure at some of the best spots Utah has to offer!

Catching these conditions has been high on my bucket list of shots to capture for a long time! I thought it would be easier, but catching the exact right density of fog with the exact right amount of wind with the exact amount of light ended up being more difficult than I realized.
•
An unfortunate series of misadventures led to me finally getting this shot. It started with me setting up my tent on top of a mountain at night in the rain, only to wake up an hour later with a severe pain in my abdomen.
•
After a couple hours of hoping the pain would magically go away, I decided to move to the inside of @missjessbess jeep hoping I would feel better if I warmed up.
•
The pain only got worse so Jess broke down her roof tent in record time in the rain at 3:00am and drove me down the bumpiest road in all of the world as I laid in the back on a dog bed until we made it back to civilization and an ER around 5:00am.
•
After distracting myself with some consistent wi-fi and meeting an army of nurses and doctors, I started feeling a little better and was told I got the pleasure of passing a gall stone.
•
Looking forward to getting back and passing out in my tent for a while, I checked myself out of the ER around 7:30am and headed back up the mountain with Jess. About 5 minutes from our campsite, the absolute perfect conditions taunted us.
•
Needless to say, we pulled over immediately, grabbed the telephoto and snagged some shots and Timelapses.
•
The price of getting this shot was steep, but if it wasn’t for the gall stone, we never would have come down the mountain, which means we wouldn’t have been coming back up the mountain in the morning to see the fog. Soooo there’s that. 🤷‍♂️
•

Shooting all day is the dream and those moody days in Colorado during fall is everything you need to make that dream come true!
•
After chasing colors all day and running endless Timelapses, we were driving the Colorado county roads on our way to our sunset location. The sun kept popping in and out creating perfect spot lit fall colors under the Rocky Mountain peaks.
•
Surrounded by 360 views, we decided to stop and make this the new sunset spot. All of a sudden the mountain gets the chefs kiss of an alpenglow. It came and went in seconds and I was stoked I was able to capture it!
•
If you want to come chase the Colorado fall colors with @missjessbess and me there’s still a few spots left in our @theimageguild workshop next month. Check out the link in my bio for more!

Today is the launch of The Rising Tide Landscape Photography Summit and I’ll be showing how you can become an army of one by incorporating ChatGPT into your photography business. •
Don’t miss out on this FREE virtual photography summit. RSVP with the link in my bio or stories and snag your spot!

Tomorrow I have the honor of speaking at Base Camp Photo Club, come listen to a color blind guy talk about color theory!
•
Discover how to capture harmonious color combinations in different lighting conditions and editing techniques that enhance color separation to create visually stunning effects. I’ll be talking about how these harmonies can be found in nature and how powerful timing and lighting is in creating captivating photographs using color to tell a story.
•
We will dive into the art of editing each color individually, from greens and reds to blues and yellows, you'll gain a deeper appreciation for the unique characteristics of each color and how to choose the right color combinations for perfect color harmony in your images.
•
Grab your spot with the link in my bio and I hope to see you there!
